metadata.description:

metadata.name: Oculus prime #9
metadata.description:
Is it an eye, a camera lens or something else entirely? We’ll never know.

Click the canvas to trigger a random shift in rotation, size and alignment. A random sound effect or chord will get triggered as well.

There are mainly 3 different sounds to obtain. A set of camera autofocus effects, and a harmonised pluck sound that comes in two different pitches and speeds.

There are a various amount of shapes and features that are randomised such as different sizes, colors, movements, thicknesses and so on.

The scene is covered in different configurations of Bloom and Noise effects. Unfortunately a lot of mobile devices are unable to handle it due to performance issues, hence I’ve been forced to disable the bloom effect on touch devices. I recommend playing with your minted specimen in a separate window on a computer in order to achieve the best look and smoothness.

@computeremotions - 2023-01-11

metadata.name: Element #77
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: Eucalyptus and Sagebrush #22
metadata.description:
Eucalyptus and Sagebrush is inspired by the eucalyptus trees and sagebrush found in California. These plants, and the hills they inhabit, have long been a source of beauty and adventure in my life, and I find myself repeatedly drawn back to them. The sunsets in coastal California are a perfect compliment to these hills, and I set out to represent that combination in this work.

Each iteration of this algorithm feels, to me, like a glimpse out of a car window on a drive up the coast, a pause on a cool morning hike, or a memory of tearing through sharp underbrush with good company.

Stylistically and texturally, I drew from landscapes rendered in oil pastels, placing thousands of tiny circles, alluding to the effect of depositing particles of color onto paper. 

I hope that this work evokes in the viewer the feelings of peace, wildness, and adventure that I feel when I watch the sun set over these hills.

Nat Sarkissian


Notes:
- Append “&mag=N” to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done. The maximum resolution seems to be limited by what your web browser allows. I have been able to output up to 11140px tall and wide using Firefox, which should be enough detail for prints up to 37x37 inches. I recommend keeping the console open while attempting larger renders. It will show you if you have attempted too large a render for your system. N can be any positive whole or decimal number greater than or equal to 1.

metadata.name: Refactor #35
metadata.description:
Future royalties are shared 50% with the original minters!

What is Refactor?

Refactor is a generative art series based on making noise with shapes while continuously rewriting the code to make it more clear and efficient. My ultimate goal was to add more variety to my generative art collections, improve my use of color, and create a work of art that the community will enjoy.

What was learned?

Rewriting code is similar to wiping off a failed oil painting. Sometimes it’s better to start over rather than waste time struggling to save what is destined to fail. The code for this token was re-written 3 times and can still be improved. Overall, I’m very pleased with the outputs and even more pleased with the knowledge and skills I developed throughout the creative process.

I learned how to create reusable custom functions for generating noise and adding borders. I also learned to construct custom shapes and overlays. Lastly, I now understand how to add rarity traits making this my first token to feature them. Good luck on minting a rare edition!

Why is there a Red Dot in the bottom corner?

The red dot is my signature for this series. It’s a shoutout to my first fxHash project titled “Red Dot”. I will continue to utilize red dots as a signature design element in future work.

About the token

- The overall canvas size is responsive based on your viewport
- Press “s” to save (image file type is SVG)
- Owners will be given priority access to future reserve lists
- Coded using p5js & SVGCanvas v2.0.3


About the Artist

Robert Matheson is a community engaged artist from Newberry, South Carolina. His work is focused on improving the health and well-being of others through the arts. In 2019 Robert established Newberry Made, a local artist & maker registry that has grown to over 180 members.

Robert's most recent creation is the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC. A creative space focused on providing NFT art education, collaboration and exhibition to help artists and the broader community benefit from emerging digital economies. Learn more at www.RobertMatheson.com and www.NonFungibleTokenMuseum.org

The owner of this NFT is granted personal use rights. For commercial use or to create derivative works, contact the artist.

metadata.name: Interdimensional Highways II #120
metadata.description:
Since the discovery of the first Interdimensional Highway, we have been getting better at charting them and improving our understanding of how they function. But we must hurry, because as we continue to prepare our vehicles, our bodies and minds for this one of a kind travel, there's still one question that remains to be answered:

Which will be our fate: to conquer... or to be conquered?

Interdimensional Highways is a two-parts series of generative artwork, showing some of the possible formations of connecting ways between multiple dimensions.

* * *

9 reserved pieces will be sent as gift to collectors who minted 4 or more pieces of Interdimensional Highways I.

metadata.name: Contort #284
metadata.description:
Contort is the result of combining several previously meaningless experiments and learnings into a single cohesive algorithm. The project comes in a variety of shapes, bends, twists, colors, and other variations.  

The artwork builds towards the end-result by rendering a fixed number of forms per frame to ensure a smooth rendering process. Rendering times can vary depending on which features are combined by the hash.
